Finally got to see it. I really enjoyed it as well. When Rey was hovering with rocks floating around her I thought they would continue with the Mary Sue crap-tastic character...

And in one line it pretty much disappeared. Not totally mind you, but for the most part it did. She still shouldn't have been as good at some things as she was in the first two of the trilogy, but I can suspend disbelief enough to be good with it. Had Anakin not been found by Qui-Gon in The Phantom Menace, would he have developed his Force Powers to a level similar to Rey at her age? I'm not sure.

I'm also okay with Rey saying she's a Skywalker. The look on her face conveyed, to me anyway, that she was unsure how to answer the question of her last name. She didn't want to say Palpatine due to what it meant to her and the only real memory she had of them was painful at best. I don't think anyone would really have remembered the Emperor's name by the time Rey came along, especially on an outer rim planet like Tatooine. After all, everyone seemed to forget about the Jedi in a relatively short span of time, at least twice according to the movies. The only parental figure she knew was Leia. You could say Han was a father figure, but he wasn't around long enough for that relationship to blossom. Luke was more of a cool uncle, but the argument could be had that he was somewhat of a father figure for her. Once she saw the approving nods from Luke and Leia, she took their name. The name of the folks who treated her like she was their daughter.

I disagree that The Last Jedi could be completely removed from the series. Yes, a lot of it was undone in The Rise of Skywalker, but you wouldn't know why certain things happened. For instance, you wouldn't fully understand when Ben and Han had their moment, and maybe get a little misty eyed. Heck, they even had the same dialog (or at least close enough that it sounded the same to me). You might also call BS when Luke pulls the X-Wing from the water because you wouldn't know where it came from. I think this movie did a fantastic job of undoing what shouldn't have happened in the last movie while still keeping some of the more important parts in tact. Just my opinion.

I really liked the scene when Jannah and Lando were talking about finding her parents together. I think that was a great setup for either a movie about their search specifically, or a series where Lando helps many of the conscripts find their families. Maybe because Lando had a child stolen from him by the Empire. Which leads me to a thought I had before seeing the movie, could Fin be a Calrissian?

snippet.textDisplay:
No offense intended here but I can't help but wonder what makes you or anyone else for that matter think they are qualified to say "That's just not Luke." ? Luke Skywalker is a character we haven't seen for almost three full decades! Do you actually think just because he was a happy man with a positive outlook at the end of return of the Jedi that meant he was supposed to stay that way forever? People change as they grow. The person you are in your 20s is never the person you are in your 60's. And optimistic people lose that perspective as they get older and the world beats them down fairly frequently. And let's not forget that the optimistic and respectful person everyone says Luke was in the original trilogy is flat out untrue. He spent most of a new Hope whining to everyone and complaining about everything that was happening and spends just about all of the first act back talking and disrespecting his uncle. I mean it literally took two murders and a destruction of property to get him to go with Obi-Wan and even then he spends most of his time continuously arguing with Han Solo! Then in the Empire strikes back he's immediately disrespectful and dismissive of Yoda to the point that Obi-Wan had to come back as a ghost voice and flat out tell him "This IS Yoda you idiot!" And even then when he begins his training he still acts dismissive and disrespectful, ignoring his teacher and disobeying his instructions right up to the moment he straight up bails to go do something that Yoda and Obi-Wan repeatedly told him was not going to work and would only make things worse. Return of the Jedi however is hard to judge since he doesn't show up for the jabba sequence until the end of it then spends The middle 3rd of the movie hanging out in tree houses with teddy bears before going to the death star and wrapping up the rest of the movie by being rude and disrespectful to the Emperor (which I'm sure we all think is OK since it was the emperor and it's OK to be rude to the villain in movies.). but if you ignore who he was talking to you realize Luke was just reverting back to his old arrogant bratty self because he was in a situation where doing so would be acceptable.

So in summary let me put it to you this way: imagine you are Luke Skywalker. You are a person who spent your whole childhood as something of an arrogant brat who only thinks about themself while continuously disrespecting your aunt and uncle, The people who took you in after your parents deaths even though doing so was basically a crime. You are a person who can return to your house one day and find it on fire with the smoldering corpses of these people who gave you a home lying dead at the front door without shedding a single tear over it and then go on with the rest of your life without ever even mentioning them again. But then you slowly start to improve yourself as you make new friends and try to forge yourself into something better so that you can help others. You struggle and you suffer but you keep fighting through it until eventually you reach your goal! You beat the bad guy, you redeem your father, you end a war, and then finally get to achieve your dream of building a new Temple and restarting the Jedi order. But then after years of success and a seemingly clear path ahead of you suddenly your nephew, your twin sister's son, your own student, your own goddamn family turns on you and in one night burns your temple to the ground and massacres every single one of your other students; he quite literally murders your life's work right in front of you... how optimistic would YOU be then? How positive would you feel about life and your role in it as you walk through the burning rubble stepping over the corpses of the children you taught? Especially when you remember that a brief moment of internal conflict as you stood over your sleeping nephew is what kick started the whole thing. Would it even matter to you at that point if it was you or if it was Ben who did the wrong thing? Or would you find yourself feeling like none of it would have ever happened if you hadn't gotten involved? All your students are dead and your entire life's work is a cinder just because you got involved. Would you find yourself thinking none of it would have happened if you had stayed out of it. If you had done nothing then you wouldn't have scared your nephew into a murder spree. If you had done nothing you wouldn't have made things worse. If you had done nothing things would be better. Maybe doing nothing is the safest thing you can do now. Maybe nothing is the only thing you should do from now on. Would you be right or would you be wrong? Or more importantly would it even matter to you anymore? When you try to look back on your youth and remember the heroic do-gooder you were but all you can see are the burning bodies of dead children and dead dreams what would you rather do? Play the blame game before going off to fight and kill another member of your family, essentially repeating your life like a record that won't stop skipping, or would you realize a 60-year-old man has no chance of repeating The glory days of his 20s and the sudden lack of any remaining students means there's no one to take your place. Because if it was me I know what I would want to do at that point. I'd just want to get the hell away from it all. I'd think every time I get involved I either fail or make everything worse. Hell I even failed back during those glory days! When it all came down to the final moment and I face the emperor as a Jedi I ended up on the ground in a smoking heap of lightning while daddy killed the bad guy for me. Have I ever truly been the hero? Or have I been wrong my entire life? I think I just want to be alone now. Maybe for a while. Maybe for a looooong while.

Seems a bit much? Well that shit happens to people every single day. And just because Star Wars is meant to be fantasy doesn't mean you can't portray characters in a realistic way. But a guy who stays chipper and heroic after half a century of fighting, failing, and repeated family betrayals? THAT's the real fantasy.

snippet.textDisplay: I think the entire scene with Kylo and Han Solo was entirely in Ben's head, which is why he told Han he was "just a memory". I'll bet if there had been anyone else there watching Kylo they wouldn't have seen him actually speaking out loud having a conversation with no one. They would have just seen him standing there quietly staring at the water while everything we saw on screen was playing out in his head. Because the writers knew they couldn't bring him back as a force ghost since he wasn't a force user but he HAD to come back somehow for Ben's redemption to actually seem plausible. Regardless of all his other evil acts throughout the series the one irredeemably evil act that was looming over him branding him "evil forever" was murdering his father. So the only way most of us would be able to accept his return to the light was if he somehow got redemption for that one specific act. So how do you do that? You bring Han Solo back. That's why the scene in question ultimately becomes Kylo replaying that moment out all over again but this time throwing away the light saber instead of stabbing his father. He can't have a real do-over so he just imagined one. That way the one unforgivable deed we were all holding over his head could be washed away and the rest of his attempt at redemption (going to join Rey, killing the knights of Ren, helping to destroy Palpatine, and literally giving his life to save Rey's...) would be something the audience could believe and accept.
